Vivian Vance (born Vivian Roberta Jones; July 26, 1909 – August 17, 1979) was an American actress and singer best known for her role as Ethel Mertz on the American television sitcom I Love Lucy, which was broadcast from 1951 to 1957. She won the Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Supporting Actress in 1954, as well as received three other Emmy nominations. She also starred as Vivian Bagley on the sitcom The Lucy Show (1962–1965) leaving in 1965 but guesting 1967–1968. Early life Vance was born Vivian Roberta Jones on July 26, 1909, in Cherryvale, Kansas, the second of six children born to Robert Andrew, Sr. and Euphemia Mae (Ragan) Jones. When she was six years old, her family moved to Independence, Kansas, where she eventually began her dramatic studies at Independence High School with drama instructor Anna Ingleman. Her love of acting clashed with her mother's strict religious beliefs. "Viv" soon rebelled, often sneaking out of her bedroom and staying out after curfew. She changed her surname to Vance and moved to Albuquerque, New Mexico, to find work as an actress. Vance performed in the very first show at the Albuquerque Little Theatre in 1930. She would go on to appear there in many other plays, including This Thing Called Love and The Cradle Song. The local theatre community helped pay her way to New York City to study under Eva Le Gallienne. ->

John Wellbelove (September 13. 1878 – November 26, 1973) was an English-born farmer and political figure in Saskatchewan. He represented Kerrobert-Kindersley from 1944 to 1956 in the Legislative Assembly of Saskatchewan as a Co-operative Commonwealth Federation (CCF) member. He was born in Berkshire, was educated at Sunningdale School and came to Canada in 1907. Wellbelove came west in 1909 and settled on a homestead near the future site of Eston, Saskatchewan. He served on the executive of the United Farmers of Canada, was a Saskatchewan Wheat Pool delegate and served on the Western Grain Standards Committee from 1927 to 1944. He also was a member of the council for the rural municipality of Snipe Lake and a member of the Eston school board; Wellbelove also served on the Board of Stewards for the Methodist Church and then for the United Church of Canada. He was deputy speaker for the provincial assembly from 1946 to 1956. ->

The organizing model, as the term refers to trade unions (and sometimes other social-movement organizations), is a broad conception of how those organizations should recruit, operate, and advance the interests of their members, though the specific functions of the model are more detailed and are discussed at length below. It typically involves many full-time organizers, who work by building up confidence and strong networks and leaders within the workforce, and by confrontational campaigns involving large numbers of union members. The organizing model is strongly linked to social movement unionism and community unionism. The organizing model contributes to the discussion of how trade unions can reverse the trend of declining membership, which they are experiencing in most industrial nations, and how they can recapture some of the political power, which the labor movement has lost over the past century. The organizing model is frequently compared and contrasted with other methods of union organization, such as the servicing model. There is disagreement as to the logistics of applying the organizing model and whether it should focus on organizing existing members, recruiting new members, or both. The prominence of the model and the debate over its worth are seen primarily in the United States, Australia, and the United Kingdom. ->

Engineering education is the activity of teaching knowledge and principles to the professional practice of engineering. It includes an initial education (bachelor's and/or master's degree), and any advanced education and specializations that follow. Engineering education is typically accompanied by additional postgraduate examinations and supervised training as the requirements for a professional engineering license. The length of education, and training to qualify as a basic professional engineer, is typically 5 years, with 15–20 years for an engineer who takes responsibility for major projects. Science, technology, engineering, and mathematics (STEM) education in primary and secondary schools often serves as the foundation for engineering education at the university level. In the United States, engineering education is a part of the STEM initiative in public schools. Service-learning in engineering education is gaining popularity within the variety of disciplinary focuses within engineering education including chemical engineering, Civil engineering, mechanical engineering, industrial engineering, computer engineering, electrical engineering, architectural engineering, and other engineering education. ->

Kuttiady is one of the villages situated in Kuttiady Taluk of Thrissur district, Kerala, India. The village is located about 10 km from Thrissur town. Kuttiady is a village located in the Kuttiady Taluk of Thrissur district in Kerala, India. The village is about 10 km from Thrissur town. The population of the village was about 2,000 in 2001. Kuttiady is known for its natural beauty and is also home to a few ancient temples. Tourist attractions in the village include the Kuttiady Rishi Parappanangal, the Kuttiady Mahadeva Temple, the Ayyappa Temple and the Kulathupuzha Perumal Temple. There are also some natural hot springs in the vicinity of the village. The economy of the village is mainly based on agriculture. A few small industries are also present. The major crops grown in the area include paddy, coconut and cashews. Animal husbandry is also an important part of the economy of the village. A few co-operative societies are also active in promoting agriculture and animal husbandry in the area. The people of Kuttiady are mainly Hindus who follow traditions such as Ayyappa puja, thiruvembar festival and kali puja. Christianity is also present in the village and following festivals like Christmas and Easter are celebrated with great fanfare. Languages spoken by the people of ->

Felix Fuld (19 July 1868 – 20 November 1951) was an Austrian-born German banker and industrialist who was a co-founder of the Deutsche Bank. Fuld was born in Vienna, Austria, the son of a cabinet maker. He started working at an early age and by the age of 17 had become a clerk in a money changer's shop. In 1892, Fuld moved to Berlin, Germany, and began working for the Dresdner Bank. In 1901, he co-founded the Deutsche Bank with Paul Warburg. The Deutsche Bank became one of the largest banks in Europe and Fuld served as its chairman from its establishment until his retirement in 1938. He also served as chairman of the board of directors of several other companies, including the Vereinigte Stahlwerke AG and the Pullach-Braunkohle-AG. Fuld was a member of several honorary committees, including the Imperial Academy of Sciences in Vienna. He died in 1951 in Pullach, Bavaria, Germany. ->

Tallgrass Beef Company is a Kansas-based beef company that sells grass fed and grass finished beef. Tallgrass Beef became the first grass fed beef producer to sell steaks in Chicago in 2005 when Harry Caray’s Restaurant began selling Tallgrass Beef. Its beef is sold via restaurants and grocery stores throughout the Midwest, East Coast, and Southeast, in addition to mail order. Tallgrass Beef Company raises some of its cattle on founder Bill Kurtis's Sedan, Kansas ranch. Tallgrass also has a network of family farmers and ranchers who raise and finish grass fed cattle that fit the standards of the Tallgrass protocols. Beef production Tallgrass' production process involves scientists employed by the company searching the United States for cattle whose genetics naturally causes the animal to fatten quickly and tenderly on grass. Beef producers have no databank of DNA with which to compare their findings, and so Tallgrass scientists use ultrasound technology to determine the tenderness of its potential herds. ->

Slideshows is the second studio album release by American singer-songwriter and musician Lana Del Rey. It was released on September 18, 2012, by Interscope Records. After releasing her debut studio album, Born to Die, in 2012, Del Rey embarked on a world tour in support of the album. During this time, she began working on her second album and recorded with several producers. The majority of the album was recorded at various studios in the United States, including Capitol Studios in Hollywood and The Magic Shop in Santa Monica. "Slideshows" is a departure from Born to Die; it is more electronic and experimental. Del Rey stated that the album's title was inspired by MTV's popular show "Slippery Slope", which is also the name of a track from the album. "NME" opined that the album's themes were "dystopian", and noted an influence from 1970s disco music. "Slideshows" was met with generally positive reviews from music critics. At Metacritic, which assigns a normalized rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream publications, the album received an average score of 66, based on 27 reviews. The album debuted at number two on the U.S. Billboard 200 chart with first-week sales of 131,000 copies. It also reached the top 10 in countries such as Canada, Denmark, Ireland, Italy, Norway and Sweden. Credits adapted from liner notes of "Slideshows". ->

Robin Olds (July 14, 1922 – June 14, 2013) was an American neurologist and pharmacologist who made significant contributions to the understanding of the role of dopamine in brain function. Olds was born on July 14, 1922 in Columbus, Ohio. He received his B.S. from Ohio State University in 1943 and his M.D. from Harvard Medical School in 1947. He served in the United States Army from 1945 to 1946 and then completed his residency at Massachusetts General Hospital. Olds began his academic career as an assistant professor at Harvard Medical School in 1952, and he became a full professor there in 1970. He served as chairman of the Department of Neurology at Harvard Medical School from 1978 to 1984, and he also served as the director of the Harvard Brain Tumor Institute from 1978 to 1984. Olds was a fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences, the American Association for the Advancement of Science, and the National Academy of Sciences. He was awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom by Ronald Reagan in 1985. He died on June 14, 2013 at the age of 92. ->

Mohammed Hussein Heikal ( ; August 20, 1922 – September 3, 2016) was an Egyptian politician and diplomat who served as Prime Minister of Egypt three times, most recently from November 14, 1981 to October 6, 1982. Heikal also served as Foreign Minister of Egypt from November 14, 1981 to October 6, 1982. Mohammed Hussein Heikal was born in 1922 in the village of al-Gharbia in the Nile Delta region of Egypt. After completing his secondary education at al-Azhar University, Heikal studied law at Cairo University. Heikal's political career began in the early 1950s when he became a member of the Wafd Party. In 1957, he was elected to the Egyptian Parliament. Heikal served as Minister of Foreign Affairs from November 14, 1981 to October 6, 1982 under President Anwar Sadat. In this role, Heikal played a major role in negotiating the Camp David Accords with Israel. Heikal later served as Prime Minister of Egypt from November 14, 1981 to October 6, 1982. In this capacity, Heikal was responsible for implementing policies designed to improve the living conditions of Egyptians and reduce unemployment. Heikal retired from active politics in 1992 and became a senior fellow at the Arab Reform Initiative. Heikal died on September 3, 2016 at the age of 94. ->

Douglas Norman "Doug" Arnold is a mathematician whose research focuses on the numerical analysis of partial differential equations with applications in mechanics and other fields in physics. , he is McKnight Presidential Professor of Mathematics at the University of Minnesota. He then moved to work at the University of Maryland, College Park. In 1989, he moved to Penn State University where he occupied a chair until 2002. He became director of the Institute for Mathematics and its Applications (IMA) in Minnesota in 2001. At the end of his term as director of the IMA, he becomes the McKnight Presidential Professor of Mathematics at the University of Minnesota. He served as president of the Society for Industrial and Applied Mathematics in 2009 and 2010. ->

Lake Tugalo is a reservoir with a surface area of and a maximum depth of . It is located in the Tugalo National Forest, east of which it is administratively divided. The lake is part of the Columbia River Basin, and lies within the US states of Oregon and Washington. Lake Tugalo is a reservoir with a surface area of . It is located in the Tugalo National Forest, east of which it is administratively divided. The lake is part of the Columbia River Basin, and lies within the US states of Oregon and Washington. The reservoir was created by the construction of the Tugalo Dam on the Columbia River approximately 25 miles upstream from the mouth of the Tugalo River. The dam created Lake Tugalo, as well as Lake Roosevelt to the southeast. Lake Roosevelt was later renamed Lake Shasta. The Bureau of Reclamation operates and maintains both reservoirs, which are used for irrigation, municipal water supplies, power generation, and recreation. The dam impounds approximately 423 million acre feet (5,500 km3) of water, making it one of the largest man-made lakes in the United States. ->

Morris Davies, (bardic name: Meurig Ebrill; 1780-1839) was a Welsh poet, dramatist and editor. Morris Davies was born in 1780 in the parish of Llanbadarn Fawr, Cardiganshire, Wales, the eldest of twelve children of William Davies, a coal-miner, and his wife Griffiths. In 1802 he was apprenticed to a cotton-spinner in Manchester, but he abandoned this career after three years to become a schoolteacher. In 1807 Davies married Martha Thomas and they moved to London, where he supported himself with teaching and writing. His early works were collections of Welsh poems, but his first important success was as the author of a comic opera called "The Devil's Charterhouse" (1810), which was performed at the Royalty Theatre. Davies then turned to dramatic writing and produced such successful pieces as "The Mayor of Garratt" (1811), "The Forty Thieves" (1812), "The Wandering Jew" (1813) and "The Betrothed" (1816). He also edited several magazines, including the "Morning Chronicle" (1817-22) and the "Athenaeum" (1824-30). Davies's later years were troubled by financial problems. In 1829 he was declared bankrupt and had to sell his house in London. He retired to Wales in 1830 and died there in 1939. ->

Gordon William Lillie (February 14, 1860 – February 3, 1942), known professionally as Pawnee Bill, was an American showman and performer who specialized in Wild West shows and was known for his short partnership with William "Buffalo" Bill Cody. In 2010, he was inducted into the Hall of Great Westerners of the National Cowboy & Western Heritage Museum. Early life and family Pawnee Bill was born on February 14, 1860, in Bloomington, Illinois. His father Newton operated a flour mill in Bloomington; the mill burned to the ground in 1876. The family then moved to Wellington, Kansas, where Gordon developed a love for the West. By the age of 19, he was working on the Pawnee Indian agency in Indian Territory. In 1883, he was given the chance to work as the Pawnee interpreter with Buffalo Bill's Wild West Show. His work with the show was the origin of his nickname as "Pawnee Bill." ->

Allen Lucas Messer (born February 27, 1969) is an American businessman and politician who currently serves as the Republican member of the United States House of Representatives for the Sixth District of Mississippi. Attilio Giordani (13 February 1913 - 18 January 2005) was an Italian economist, and Professor Emeritus at the University of Bologna. He was a leading figure in the development of macroeconomics and was instrumental in the revival of Keynesian economics. Attilio Giordani was born on 13 February 1913 in Bologna, Italy. He received his undergraduate degree in political science from the University of Bologna in 1935, and his doctorate in economics from the University of Cambridge in 1939. He joined the University of Bologna faculty in 1941 as an assistant professor, and became a full professor there in 1964. Giordani's research focused on macroeconomics and monetary economics. His seminal work, "The Theory of Money and Credit" (1944), introduced the now-standard Keynesian model of interest rates and aggregate demand. He also developed an important theory of price determination, known as the Giordani-Modigliani equation. Giordani served as president of the European Economic Association (EurEA) from 1966 to 1967, and as president of the International Economic Association (IEA) from 1971 to 1972. He was also a member of the Italian Academy of Science and Engineering, and a fellow of both the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and the Royal Society of London. Attilio Giordani died on 18 January 2005 at the age of 94. ->

Republic Square is an urban park in central Austin, Texas. Located in Downtown Austin, the park features a grassy area meant for festivals and events as well as shaded areas under live oak trees. History Originally called "Hamilton Square", Republic Square was one of four public squares laid out in the 1839 Waller Plan of Austin by Edwin Waller. The square functioned as a normal urban park up until the mid-twentieth century when it served as a parking lot. The neighborhood surrounding the park became significant for its Mexican American residents in throughout the late 1800s and early 1900s. During the United States Bicentennial, the city of Austin transformed the square to its former glory, and was later revitalized again in 2017. Despite many physical changes, the historic heritage Auction Oaks survived and remain a centerpiece to the square till this day. ->

Peter Alexis Boodberg (born Pyotr Alekseyevich Budberg; September 7, 1931 – March 21, 2004) was a Russian-born American mathematician, who made important contributions to the theory of Lie groups and their applications. Boodberg was born in Leningrad (now Saint Petersburg), the son of Pyotr Alekseyevich Budberg and Olga Voronovna. He received his Ph.D. in mathematics from Moscow State University in 1955 under the supervision of Vladimir Arnold Zilber. From 1955 to 1960 he was a postdoctoral fellow at Princeton University under the direction of John von Neumann and Murray Schumaker. From 1960 to 1962 he was an instructor at Brown University, and from 1962 to 1966 an associate professor at Columbia University. In 1968 he became a full professor at the University of California, Berkeley, where he remained until his death. Boodberg is perhaps best known for his work on Lie groups and their applications, in which he made important advances in understanding the structure of these mathematical objects. His most influential papers on this subject include "On a theorem of Artin and its application to semisimple Lie groups" (1961), "The structure of simple Lie groups" (1963), and "On a property of simple Lie group representations" (1977). Boodberg also made significant contributions to the theory of dynamical systems, including work on chaos theory and bifurcation theory. In particular, his paper "Chaos and dissipative structures" ->

Jerome Adams "Jerry" Utley (January 7, 1881 – October 15, 1966) was an American professional baseball player who played in Major League Baseball (MLB) for the Philadelphia Phillies and Boston Braves from 1905 to 1917. Utley was born in West Chester, Pennsylvania, and played his first professional season with the minor league Johnstown team of the Appalachian League in 1902. He made his MLB debut with the Phillies in 1905 and led the National League (NL) in batting average in 1907, 1908, and 1911. He won three NL batting titles, led the NL in hits four times, and finished second twice. In 1912, Utley led the Phillies to their first pennant championship and their first World Series appearance. The Phillies lost to the New York Giants in five games. In 1916, he joined the Braves and led them to their first NL pennant. The Braves lost to the Chicago Cubs in six games in the World Series. Utley finished his MLB career with a .325 batting average, 521 home runs, 1,676 RBIs, and 1,955 runs scored. He also had a .929 fielding percentage at first base. He was inducted into the Baseball Hall of Fame in 1955. Utley was a vocal opponent of baseball's reserve clause system and participated in an antitrust suit against MLB that was ultimately unsuccessful. After his playing career ended, Utley served as a coach for ->

Blandina Segale, more commonly known as Sister Blandina (23 January 1850 – 23 February 1941) was an Italian-born American Sister of Charity of Cincinnati and missionary, who became widely known through her service on the American frontier in the late 19th century. During her missionary work, she met, among others, Billy the Kid and the leaders of the Native American tribes of the Apache and Comanche. She served as an educator and social worker who worked in Ohio, Colorado and New Mexico, assisting Native Americans, Hispanic settlers and European immigrants. The Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Santa Fe has opened a process to canonize Segale, for which it has received the permission of the Holy See. For this, she is honored by the Catholic Church with the title of Servant of God. She is the first individual in New Mexico's 400-year history with the Roman Catholic Church to have a cause opened for their beatification and canonization. ->

Jan Mühlstein (born 3 July 1949 in Most, Czechoslovakia) is a journalist, German Jewish activist and the former chair of the Union of Progressive Jews in Germany. Life Jan Mühlstein grew up in a German-speaking Jewish family, which traditionally practised Liberal Judaism. In 1967, he began studying physics at the Karl University in Prague. After the defeat of the reformation movement known as the Prague Spring, in which Mühlstein participated actively, he emigrated to West Germany in 1969. From 1970 onwards, he studied physics at the Ludwig Maximilians University in Munich and completed a Ph.D. in theoretical quantum optics in 1977. During the next four years, he worked in the leadership of project energy research of the nuclear energy research facility in Jülich. Since 1982 Mühlstein has been working as a business journalist in Munich and is deputy chief editor of a journal covering the economics of the energy market. ->

Abdul Muhaimin Iskandar (born 24 September 1966), also known as Iskandar Muda, is the current Prime Minister of Malaysia. He is the youngest ever Prime Minister in Malaysian history, and the second youngest after the current ruler Sultan Muhammad V. Iskandar was first elected to Parliament in 1998, becoming a member of the United Malays National Organisation (UMNO) party. He was appointed Deputy Prime Minister in 2001, and served in that role until 2002, when he was appointed Finance Minister. He became Health Minister in 2004, and held that position until 2006. In 2007, he was appointed Deputy Prime Minister again, this time in charge of the Home Affairs Ministry. In 2009, he became Deputy Prime Minister once again, this time in charge of the Defence Ministry. In 2013, he was appointed Defence Minister for a second time. On 10 March 2016, Iskandar was elected as Prime Minister after defeating incumbent Najib Razak in a general election. ->

He worked extensively as an accompanist for vocalists, starting with Peggy Lee in 1949–1950; he also played behind Tony Bennett and Anita O'Day. He recorded with Lena Horne multiple times in the late 1950s and early 1960s and also accompanied her on tours of Europe. During this time, he also worked with his own small groups; his sidemen included Danny Bank, Johnny Carisi, Bill Crow, Tony Fruscella, and Dave Schildkraut. He began working more as a studio musician and film score composer in the 1960s. Toward the end of the decade he played with Carmen McRae, then moved to Canada to take a position as a house pianist with the CBC in Toronto. In the 1980s he worked with Ruby Braff and toured and recorded in Japan, and continued to be active as a performer into the 1990s, working with James Campbell, Don Thompson, Memo Acevedo, Dave Young, and Terry Clarke. ->

The Ghoryakhel is a Pashtun supertribe that inhabits the North-West Frontier Province and Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, Pakistan. The Ghoryakhel are a sub-tribe of the Kalash. They speak the Ghoryakhel language, which is closely related to the Pashto language. The Ghoryakhel trace their ancestry back to the Prophet Muhammad's grandson Ali ibn Abi Talib, through his son Hasan ibn Ali. The Ghoryakhel are believed to have migrated from central Asia in the 12th century AD. The Ghoryakhel settled in what is now the North-West Frontier Province and Khyber Pakhtunkhwa. They are Sunni Muslimpractising the Hanafi school of Islamic jurisprudence. The Ghoryakhel are a agricultural people and are known for their goat herding skills. They also engage in livestock farming, growing wheat, maize, peas, and other crops. The Ghoryakhel are also skilled in handicrafts such as weaving carpets and mats, making pottery, and creating silver jewelry. ->

Voogt is a Dutch surname. In modern Dutch, it is usually pronounced "voogt". The name originated from a Germanic personal name, cognate with the English word "wolf". The surname Voogt is distributed throughout the Netherlands, but is especially prevalent in the provinces of North Brabant and Limburg. The Voogt family was one of the most important noble families in the Middle Ages. They played a prominent role in Dutch history, most notably as generals during the Dutch Revolt and as governors of the Dutch East Indies. The Voogt family also had a long tradition of service in the Catholic Church. The Voogt family first appeared in written records in 1264 as de Vocht. They were a prominent family in the region of Maastricht and led a turbulent life. In 1290, they were implicated in a plot to overthrow William II of Holland. They fled to France but were eventually pardoned and returned to Holland. The Voogts rose to prominence during the Middle Ages. In 1339, they obtained land near Heusden-Zolder from Louis II, Count of Flanders. This became known as the Voogtland. The Voogts became one of the most powerful families in Holland and held many important positions in government. They were frequently involved in military campaigns and played a major role in Dutch history. The Voogts were particularly influential during the Dutch Revolt. As generals, they played a vital ->

During his time as sheriff, Madigan made major changes to the department, instituting new training procedures, modernizing the department's equipment and creating a centralized fingerprint identification system. He also oversaw a significant increase in law enforcement resources in Alameda County. After leaving office, Madigan served as a mediator and arbitrator for the county government. The America Line (German: Amerikalinie) is the primary name of the Hamburg S-Bahn line S2 that links the city of Hamburg to its neighbouring cities in northern Germany. It is also known as the Köln-Hamburg Line and the Rhein-Neckar-Bahn. The America Line is a long railway line that runs between Hamburg and Cologne, with intermediate stops in Neuss, Düsseldorf, Essen and Duisburg. The line is 322 kilometres (200 miles) long, making it one of the longest railway lines in Germany. The line was opened on 15 December 1842, as part of a project to connect Hamburg and Cologne. At the time, it was the longest railway line in Europe. The first section of the line from Hamburg to Neuss was opened on 1 July 1843. The section from Neuss to Düsseldorf was opened on 1 August 1844. The section from Düsseldorf to Essen was opened on 1 October 1844. The section from Essen to Duisburg was opened on 5 May 1846. The final section of the line from Duisburg to Cologne was opened on 10 May 1846. Today, the America Line is one of the busiest railway lines in Germany. It carries over 470,000 passengers each day. ->

Myingyan is a city and district in the Mandalay Division of central Myanmar, previously, it was a district in the Meiktila Division of Upper Burma. It is currently the capital of Myingyan Township and lies along the National Highway 2. , the city had a population of 276,096 and the district had 1,055,957. It lies in the valley of the Ayeyarwady River, to the south of Mandalay, on the east bank of the river. The area around the town is flat, especially to the north and along the banks of the Ayeyarwady. Inland the country rises in gently undulating slopes. The most noticeable feature is Popa Hill, an extinct volcano, to the south-east. The highest peak is . above sea-level. The climate is dry, with high south winds from March until September. The annual rainfall averages about . The temperature varies between . The ordinary crops are millet, sesame, cotton, maize, rice and a great variety of peas and beans. There are no forests, but a great deal of low scrubland. Myingyan is the head of the branch railway to Thazi and the main line between Yangon and Mandalay. ->

Jean-Claude Milner (; born 3 January 1941) is a French entrepreneur, investor, and philanthropist. He is the chairman and chief executive officer (CEO) of the investment company, Evercore Partners. He is also a co-founder of the technology conglomerate, Atomico. Born in Paris, Milner attended high school at the Lycée Français de New York City and then studied mathematics and economics at the École Polytechnique and the École Nationale d'Administration (ENA), both in Paris. Since 1987, Milner has been a member of the French Academy of Sciences. He was knighted in 2002 for services to business and entrepreneurship. Milner has been married to Jacqueline since 1966. An indoor positioning system (IPS) is a wireless local area network (WLAN) technology that uses an adjustable antenna to determine the location of a user indoors. IPS systems are used in commercial and residential environments to provide location information for applications such as real-time mapping, indoor navigation, and social networking. IPS systems use two primary methods to determine a user's location: triangulation and time of flight (ToF). Triangulation uses the geometrical properties of walls and objects in the environment to calculate a user's position. ToF uses the time it takes for a radio wave to travel between two points and calculate a user's distance. IPS systems can be divided into three categories based on how they collect location data: peer-to-peer, client-server, and centralized. Peer-to-peer IPS systems use multiple users' devices to share location data. Client-server IPS systems use one device to collect and store all the location data. Centralized IPS systems use a server to collect and store all the location data. IPS systems are commonly used in commercial buildings, such as airports, hospitals, shopping malls, and schools. They are also used in residential buildings, such as homes, apartments, and condominiums. ->

John Rucho (November 22, 1922 – February 22, 2015) was a member of the Massachusetts House of Representatives and an American businessman. Born in Providence, Rhode Island, he moved with his family to Worcester, Massachusetts. He went to Commerce High School and Becker Junior College. From 1942-1945, Rucho served in the United States Navy in World War II as a 3rd class petty officer and a combat veteran on the USS Custer and Newberry, and courageously fought on an amphibious assault squadron at Iwo Jima, Okinawa, and the Marshall Islands. Upon returning he went to Simmons School of Floral Design in Wellesley, Massachusetts. In 1946, Rucho along with his brothers opened Dian's Flower Shop in Worcester, Ma. In 1967, Rucho embarked on another venture with the establishment of Crest Jewelers in Worcester. From 1973 to 1979, Rucho served as a Democrat in the Massachusetts House of Representatives from the Main South region and served for three terms. He served on the Joint Committee on Post Audit and Oversight and the Committees on Election Laws and State Administration. He filed legislation in areas of welfare reform, property tax relief, and campaign financing. He also served a term as Commissioner of Hope Cemetery. After his political career he continued working as a public servant for the Worcester County, Massachusetts Sheriff department until retirement. Upon retirement Rucho spent his remaining years residing in both St. Petersburg, FL and Worcester, Ma. ->

Patty Loveless (born Patricia Lee Ramey; January 4, 1957), is an American country music singer. She has also released 16 studio albums; in the United States, four of these albums have been certified platinum by the Recording Industry Association of America (RIAA), and two have been certified gold. Levi Underwood (December 24, 1821 – March 11, 1902) was a lawyer and politician from Vermont. Originally a Democrat, Underwood's antislavery views caused him to join the new Republican Party when it was founded. Underwood was most notable for his service as the 23rd lieutenant governor of Vermont from 1860 to 1862. A native of Hardwick, Vermont, Underwood was raised and educated in Hardwick, studied law, and attained admission to the bar in 1842. A longtime resident of Burlington, Underwood was also active in railroads, banking, and insurance. Originally a Democrat, he served in local offices including justice of the peace. He was State's Attorney of Chittenden County from 1852 to 1854. He joined the new Republican party at its founding, served as president of its 1856 state convention, and was a delegate to the 1856 Republican National Convention. In September 1856, Underwood was elected to a one-year term in the Vermont Senate, and he served from October 1856 to October 1857. ->

Susannah Caroline Constantine (born 3 June 1962) is a British journalist, author and broadcaster. Constantine was born in London, the daughter of Joanne (née Bickley), a writer, and Denis Constantine, a journalist and television executive. She was educated at Westminster School and Wadham College, Oxford where she read History. After graduation Constantine worked for the "Daily Express" as a trainee reporter. She moved to "The Observer" in 1986 and became a feature writer. In 1990 she became deputy political editor of "The Observer". In 1991 she was appointed political correspondent of "The Independent" and in 1992 she became political editor of "The Independent on Sunday". In 1997 Constantine founded the independent television company Channel 4 News. She left Channel 4 News in 2003 to become director of communications for Tony Blair's government. In 2004 she published her autobiography, "A Life of Power", which won the William Hill Book of the Year Award. Since leaving government Constantine has been a freelance journalist writing for "The Guardian", "The Daily Telegraph", "The Sunday Times", "New Statesman" and other newspapers. She has also been a regular commentator on BBC1's The Andrew Marr Show and Sky News' Murnaghan programme. Constantine is also a regular contributor to Radio 4's Today programme. In 2006 Constantine published her second book, "Queen: The Official Biography of Elizabeth II". It was widely praised by reviewers for its access to sources previously unavailable to biographers and ->

The ATI Wonder series represents some of the first video card add-on products for IBM Personal Computers and compatibles introduced by ATI Technologies in the mid to late 1980s. These cards were unique at the time as they offered the end user a considerable amount of value by combining support for multiple graphics standards (and monitors) into a single card. The VGA Wonder series added additional value with the inclusion of a bus mouse port, which normally required the installation of a dedicated Microsoft Mouse adapter. The VGA Wonder series later merged with the ATI Mach series of cards in 1990. The ATI Graphics Ultra (VRAM) and ATI Graphics Vantage (DRAM) cards both featured independent VGA Wonder ASICs in addition to their Mach8 8514 compatible graphics processor. The Graphics Ultra was later renamed the VGA Wonder GT. In 1992, their following product line, the Mach32, integrated the VGA wonder core and coprocessor into a single IC. At this point the VGA Wonder line was cancelled and replaced with a cost reduced DRAM based version of Mach32 known as the "ATI Graphics Wonder". ->

Timothy Raymond Naish is a New Zealand glaciologist and climate scientist who has been a researcher and lecturer at Victoria University of Wellington and the Director of the Antarctic Research Centre, and in 2020 became a programme leader at the Antarctic Science Platform. Naish has researched and written about the possible effect of melting ice sheets in Antarctica on global sea levels due to high CO emissions causing warming in the Southern Ocean. He was instrumental in establishing and leading the Antarctica Drilling Project (ANDRILL), and a Lead Author on the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) 5th Assessment Report (2014). Education and career Naish initially studied engineering at Waikato University but moved into earth sciences and gained skills in geological mapping and describing rocks, graduating with a BSc in 1988. He continued to study at Waikato University, completing a Masters Degree with first class honours in 1990 and after working for while as a geologist with the Department of Scientific and Industrial Research (DSIR) completed his PhD in 1996. He worked as an Assistant Lecturer at University of Waikato, Earth Sciences, New Zealand (1990-1995), completed the Australian Research Council Post-Doctoral Fellowship, James Cook University of Northern Queensland (1996-1997) and was Researcher and Principal Scientist at GNS Science, Lower Hutt New Zealand (1998-2016). Qualified as a professor in Earth Sciences, Naish was Director of the Antarctic Research Centre at Victoria University of Wellington from 2008 until 2017, when he took up a Royal Society of New Zealand James Cook Fellowship. He joined the leadership team of The Antarctic Science Platform in 2019. ->

Max von Gagern (b. Weilburg (in Nassau), 6 November 1861; d. Munich, 25 October 1934) was a German Field Marshal and World War I hero. Max von Gagern was born in the Free City of Weilburg in the Grand Duchy of Nassau into a Prussian family. He entered the Prussian military academy in 1878, and after graduation served with the VIIth Infantry Regiment in the German protectorate of East Africa (today's Tanzania). He saw action in the German colonial war in East Africa, where he distinguished himself as a daring and successful cavalry officer. In 1891 he was made a captain and transferred to the 8th Hussars. He served with this regiment on the outbreak of World War I, initially as regimental adjutant, and later becoming commanding officer. At the Battle of Liège on 26 August 1914, Gagern led his regiment into heavy fire and captured several positions despite being outnumbered eight to one. For his actions at Liège he was promoted to major general on 3 September 1914. He later commanded III Corps at the Battle of Verdun from February to May 1916, and at the Battle of Passchendaele from July to November 1917. He was made a field marshal on 18 October 1917.
